# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: box2d-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] Box2D was first released as "Box2D Lite", a demonstration engine to accompany a physics presentation given by Erin Catto at GDC 2006.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] On September 11, 2007, it was released as open source on SourceForge.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] On January 17, 2010, Box 2D moved the project to Google Code for hosting.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] On July 12, 2015, hosting was moved again, this time to GitHub.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] On March 6, 2008, version 2.0 was launched, introducing continuous collision detection and revamping the API.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] On July 27, 2020, version 2.4 was launched, with a variety of changes, most notably the license was changed to the MIT License.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] On Aug 12, 2024, version 3.0 was launched, rewriting the library entirely in C, overhauling the API, increasing single and multi-threaded performance, and changing to a more stable physics solver.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] Box2D is itself written in platform-independent C (usable on any system with a C compiler available).
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] The engine may be compiled in fixed point and floating point modes, and has been used on the Nintendo DS, Wii, and several mobile phones (including Android, BlackBerry 10 and iOS) as well as most major operating systems.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] The engine has been ported to many other programming languages and environments, including Java, Adobe Flash (in ActionScript and Haxe languages), C#, Lua, JavaScript, and D.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] Bindings exist to use the compiled library from Python, DarkBASIC and BBC BASIC.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] On October 30, 2009, it was announced that Box2D was being integrated into the (now older) Torque 2D game engine.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] Box2D performs constrained rigid body simulation.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] It can simulate bodies composed of convex polygons, circles, and edge shapes.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] Bodies are joined with joints and acted upon by forces.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] The engine also applies gravity, friction, and restitution.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] Box2D's collision detection and resolution system consists of three pieces: an incremental sweep and prune broad phase, a continuous collision detection unit, and a stable linear-time contact solver.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] These algorithms allow efficient simulations of fast bodies and large stacks without missing collisions or causing instabilities.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] An earlier version of the Box2D engine, now known as Box2D Lite, was released primarily for educational purposes, based on a series of yearly Game Developers Conference presentations that Erin Catto has given.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] Box2D Lite uses many of the same algorithms as Box2D, but has a smaller feature set.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] The Chipmunk physics engine (written in C) and Phys2D (written in Java) are both partially based on Box2D Lite.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] The physics engine used in SpriteKit for iOS and OS X uses Box2D internally.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] The LiquidFun physics engine is a fork of Box2D by Google, which adds fluid simulation to the engine.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] LibGDX uses a Java wrapper around native Box2D code written in C as its physics engine.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] Itterheim and Wenderlich describe the usage of Box2D in the Cocos2d iPhone engine.
[src:box2d-physics/box2d] An article in the Adobe Edge newsletter discusses the use of Box2D in Flash games.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] In the context of classical mechanics simulations and physics engines employed within video games, **collision response** deals with models and algorithms for simulating the changes in the motion of two solid bodies following collision and other forms of contact.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Two rigid bodies in unconstrained motion, potentially under the action of forces, may be modelled by solving their equations of motion using numerical integration techniques.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] On collision, the kinetic properties of two such bodies seem to undergo an instantaneous change, typically resulting in the bodies rebounding away from each other, sliding, or settling into relative static contact, depending on the elasticity of the materials and the configuration of the collision.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The origin of the rebound phenomenon, or *reaction*, may be traced to the behaviour of real bodies that, unlike their perfectly rigid idealised counterparts, do undergo minor compression on collision, followed by expansion, prior to separation.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The compression phase converts the kinetic energy of the bodies into potential energy and to an extent, heat.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The expansion phase converts the potential energy back to kinetic energy.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The degree of relative kinetic energy retained after a collision, termed the *restitution*, is dependent on the elasticity of the bodies‟ materials.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The coefficient of restitution between two given materials is modeled as the ratio $e\in [0..1]$ of the relative post-collision speed of a point of contact along the contact normal, with respect to the relative pre-collision speed of the same point along the same normal.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] These coefficients are typically determined empirically for different material pairs, such as wood against concrete or rubber against wood.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Values for e close to zero indicate inelastic collisions such as a piece of soft clay hitting the floor, whereas values close to one represent highly elastic collisions, such as a rubber ball bouncing off a wall.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The kinetic energy loss is relative to one body with respect to the other.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Thus the total momentum of both bodies with respect to some common reference is unchanged after the collision, in line with the principle of *conservation of momentum*.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Another important contact phenomenon is surface-to-surface friction, a force that impedes the relative motion of two surfaces in contact, or that of a body in a fluid.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] In this section we discuss surface-to-surface friction of two bodies in relative static contact or sliding contact.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] In the real world, friction is due to the imperfect microstructure of surfaces whose protrusions interlock into each other, generating reactive forces tangential to the surfaces.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] To overcome the friction between two bodies in static contact, the surfaces must somehow lift away from each other.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Once in motion, the degree of surface affinity is reduced and hence bodies in sliding motion tend to offer lesser resistance to motion.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] These two categories of friction are respectively termed *static friction* and *dynamic friction*.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] It is a force which is applied to an object by another object or by a person.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The direction of the applied force depends on how the force is applied.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] It is the support force exerted upon an object which is in contact with another stable object.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Normal force is sometimes referred to as the pressing force since its action presses the surface together.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Normal force is always directed towards the object and acts perpendicularly with the applied force.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] It is the force exerted by a surface as an object moves across it or makes an effort to move across it.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The friction force opposes the motion of the object.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Friction results when two surfaces are pressed together closely, causing attractive intermolecular forces between the molecules of the two different surface.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] As such, friction depends upon the nature of the two surfaces and upon the degree to which they are pressed together.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Friction always acts parallel to the surface in contact and opposite the direction of motion.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The friction force can be calculated using the equation.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] For fixed impulse $\mathbf {j}$ , the equation suggests that $t_{1}\rightarrow t_{0}\Rightarrow \left|\mathbf {f} \right|\rightarrow \infty$ , that is, a smaller time interval must be compensated by a stronger reaction force to achieve the same impulse.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] When modelling a collision between idealized rigid bodies, it is impractical to simulate the compression and expansion phases of the body geometry over the collision time interval.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] exists and is equal to $\mathbf {j}$ , the notion of *instantaneous impulses* may be introduced to simulate an instantaneous change in velocity after a collision.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] By deduction from the principle of action and reaction, if the collision impulse applied by the first body on the second body at a contact point $\mathbf {p} _{r}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is $\mathbf {j} _{r}$ , the counter impulse applied by the second body on the first is $-\mathbf {j} _{r}$ .
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] In the subsequent formulas, $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ is always assumed to point away from body 1 and towards body 2 at the contact point.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] where, for the i th body, $\mathbf {v} _{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is the pre-collision linear velocity, $\mathbf {v'} _{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is the post-collision linear velocity.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Compute the reaction impulse vector $\mathbf {j} _{r}$ in terms of its magnitude $j_{r}$ and contact normal $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ using $\mathbf {j} _{r}=j_{r}\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] One of the most popular models for describing friction is the Coulomb friction model.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] This model defines coefficients of static friction ${\mu }_{s}\in \mathbb {R}$ and dynamic friction ${\mu }_{d}\in \mathbb {R}$ such that ${\mu }_{s}>{\mu }_{d}$ .
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] These coefficients describe the two types of friction forces in terms of the reaction forces acting on the bodies.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The value $f_{s}$ defines a maximum magnitude for the friction force required to counter the tangential component of any external sum force applied on a relatively static body, such that it remains static.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Thus, if the external force is large enough, static friction is unable to fully counter this force, at which point the body gains velocity and becomes subject to dynamic friction of magnitude $f_{d}$ acting against the sliding velocity.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The Coulomb friction model effectively defines a friction cone within which the tangential component of a force exerted by one body on the surface of another in static contact, is countered by an equal and opposite force such that the static configuration is maintained.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Conversely, if the force falls outside the cone, static friction gives way to dynamic friction.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] where $\mathbf {f} _{e}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ is the sum of all external forces on the body.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] The multi-case definition of $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ is required for robustly computing the actual friction force $\mathbf {f} _{f}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ for both the general and particular states of contact.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Informally, the first case computes the tangent vector along the relative velocity component perpendicular to the contact normal $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] If this component is zero, the second case derives $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ in terms of the tangent component of the external force $\mathbf {f} _{e}\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] If there is no tangential velocity or external forces, then no friction is assumed, and $\mathbf {\hat {t}}$ may be set to the zero vector.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Equations (6a), (6b), (7) and (8) describe the Coulomb friction model in terms of forces.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] where $j_{r}=|\mathbf {j} _{r}|$ is the magnitude of the reaction impulse acting along contact normal $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ .
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] Equations (5) and (10) define an impulse-based contact model that is ideal for impulse-based simulations.
[src:box2d-physics/collision-response] When using this model, care must be taken in the choice of ${\mu }_{s}$ and ${\mu }_{d}$ as higher values may introduce additional kinetic energy into the system.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Friction can have dramatic consequences, as illustrated by the use of friction created by rubbing pieces of wood together to start a fire.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Another important consequence of many types of friction can be wear, which may lead to performance degradation or damage to components.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] It is known that frictional energy losses account for about 20% of the total energy expenditure of the world.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] There are many different contributors to the retarding force in friction, ranging from asperity deformation to the generation of charges and changes in local structure.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] When two bodies in contact move relative to each other, due to these various contributors some mechanical energy is transformed to heat, the free energy of structural changes, and other types of dissipation.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The total dissipated energy per unit distance moved is the **retarding frictional force**, *F=E/d*.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The complexity of the interactions involved makes the calculation of friction from first principles difficult, and it is often easier to use empirical methods for analysis and the development of theory.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Many ancient authors including Aristotle, Vitruvius, and Pliny the Elder, were interested in the cause and mitigation of friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] They were aware of differences between static and kinetic friction with Themistius stating in 350 A.D. that "it is easier to further the motion of a moving body than to move a body at rest".
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The classic laws of sliding friction were discovered by Leonardo da Vinci in 1493, a pioneer in tribology, but the laws documented in his notebooks were not published and remained unknown.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] These laws were rediscovered by Guillaume Amontons in 1699 and became known as Amonton's three laws of dry friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Amontons presented the nature of friction in terms of surface irregularities and the force required to raise the weight pressing the surfaces together.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This view was further elaborated by Bernard Forest de Bélidor and Leonhard Euler (1750), who derived the angle of repose of a weight on an inclined plane and first distinguished between static and kinetic friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] John Theophilus Desaguliers (1734) first recognized the role of adhesion in friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Microscopic forces cause surfaces to stick together; he proposed that friction was the force necessary to tear the adhering surfaces apart.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The understanding of friction was further developed by Charles-Augustin de Coulomb (1785).
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Coulomb investigated the influence of four main factors on friction: the nature of the materials in contact and their surface coatings, the extent of the surface area, the normal pressure (or load), and the length of time that the surfaces remained in contact (time of repose).
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Coulomb further considered the influence of sliding velocity, temperature and humidity, in order to decide between the different explanations on the nature of friction that had been proposed.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The distinction between static and dynamic friction is made in Coulomb's friction law (see below), although this distinction was already drawn by Johann Andreas von Segner in 1758.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The effect of the time of repose was explained by Pieter van Musschenbroek (1762) by considering the surfaces of fibrous materials, with fibers meshing together, which takes a finite time in which the friction increases.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] John Leslie (1766–1832) noted a weakness in the views of Amontons and Coulomb: If friction arises from a weight being drawn up the inclined plane of successive asperities, then why is it not balanced through descending the opposite slope?
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Leslie was equally skeptical about the role of adhesion proposed by Desaguliers, which should on the whole have the same tendency to accelerate as to retard the motion.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In Leslie's view, friction should be seen as a time-dependent process of flattening, pressing down asperities, which creates new obstacles in what were cavities before.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In the long course of the development of the law of conservation of energy and of the first law of thermodynamics, friction was recognised as a mode of conversion of mechanical work into heat.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In 1798, Benjamin Thompson reported on cannon boring experiments.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Arthur Jules Morin (1833) developed the concept of sliding versus rolling friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In 1842, Julius Robert Mayer frictionally generated heat in paper pulp and measured the temperature rise.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Osborne Reynolds (1866) derived the equation of viscous flow.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This completed the classic empirical model of friction (static, kinetic, and fluid) commonly used today in engineering.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Ewing investigated the continuity between static and kinetic friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Bryan published an investigation of the foundations of thermodynamics, *Thermodynamics: an Introductory Treatise dealing mainly with First Principles and their Direct Applications*.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] He noted that for a rough body driven over a rough surface, the mechanical work done by the driver exceeds the mechanical work received by the surface.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The lost work is accounted for by heat generated by friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Over the years, for example in his 1879 thesis, but particularly in 1926, Planck advocated regarding the generation of heat by rubbing as the most specific way to define heat, and the prime example of an irreversible thermodynamic process.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The focus of research during the 20th century has been to understand the physical mechanisms behind friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Frank Philip Bowden and David Tabor (1950) showed that, at a microscopic level, the actual area of contact between surfaces is a very small fraction of the apparent area.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This actual area of contact, caused by asperities increases with pressure.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The development of the atomic force microscope (ca.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] 1986) enabled scientists to study friction at the atomic scale, showing that, on that scale, dry friction is the product of the inter-surface shear stress and the contact area.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] These two discoveries explain Amonton's first law *(below)*; the macroscopic proportionality between normal force and static frictional force between dry surfaces.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Dry friction resists relative lateral motion of two solid surfaces in contact.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The two regimes of dry friction are 'static friction' ("stiction") between non-moving surfaces, and *kinetic friction* (sometimes called sliding friction or dynamic friction) between moving surfaces.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The force of friction is always exerted in a direction that opposes movement (for kinetic friction) or potential movement (for static friction) between the two surfaces.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] For example, a curling stone sliding along the ice experiences a kinetic force slowing it down.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] For an example of potential movement, the drive wheels of an accelerating car experience a frictional force pointing forward; if they did not, the wheels would spin, and the rubber would slide backwards along the pavement.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Note that it is not the direction of movement of the vehicle they oppose, it is the direction of (potential) sliding between tire and road.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Coulomb friction, named after Charles-Augustin de Coulomb, is an approximate model used to calculate the force of dry friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The Coulomb friction $F_{\mathrm {f} }$ may take any value from zero up to $\mu F_{\mathrm {n} }$ , and the direction of the frictional force against a surface is opposite to the motion that surface would experience in the absence of friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Thus, in the static case, the frictional force is exactly what it must be in order to prevent motion between the surfaces; it balances the net force tending to cause such motion.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In this case, rather than providing an estimate of the actual frictional force, the Coulomb approximation provides a threshold value for this force, above which motion would commence.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This maximum force is known as traction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Static friction is friction between two or more solid objects that are not moving relative to each other.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] For example, static friction can prevent an object from sliding down a sloped surface.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The coefficient of static friction, typically denoted as *μ*s, is usually higher than the coefficient of kinetic friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Static friction is considered to arise as the result of surface roughness features across multiple length scales at solid surfaces.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] These features, known as asperities are present down to nano-scale dimensions and result in true solid to solid contact existing only at a limited number of points accounting for only a fraction of the apparent or nominal contact area.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The linearity between applied load and true contact area, arising from asperity deformation, gives rise to the linearity between static frictional force and normal force, found for typical Amonton–Coulomb type friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The static friction force must be overcome by an applied force before an object can move.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The maximum possible friction force between two surfaces before sliding begins is the product of the coefficient of static friction and the normal force: $F_{\text{max}}=\mu _{\mathrm {s} }F_{\text{n}}$ .
[src:box2d-physics/friction] When there is no sliding occurring, the friction force can have any value from zero up to $F_{\text{max}}$ .
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Any force smaller than $F_{\text{max}}$ attempting to slide one surface over the other is opposed by a frictional force of equal magnitude and opposite direction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Any force larger than $F_{\text{max}}$ overcomes the force of static friction and causes sliding to occur.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The instant sliding occurs, static friction is no longer applicable—the friction between the two surfaces is then called kinetic friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] However, an apparent static friction can be observed even in the case when the true static friction is zero.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] An example of static friction is the force that prevents a car wheel from slipping as it rolls on the ground.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Even though the wheel is in motion, the patch of the tire in contact with the ground is stationary relative to the ground, so it is static rather than kinetic friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Upon slipping, the wheel friction changes to kinetic friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] An anti-lock braking system operates on the principle of allowing a locked wheel to resume rotating so that the car maintains static friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The maximum value of static friction, when motion is impending, is sometimes referred to as **limiting friction**, although this term is not used universally.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The normal force is defined as the net force compressing two parallel surfaces together, and its direction is perpendicular to the surfaces.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In the simple case of a mass resting on a horizontal surface, the only component of the normal force is the force due to gravity, where $N=mg\,$ .
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In this case, conditions of equilibrium tell us that the magnitude of the friction force is *zero*, $F_{f}=0$ .
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In fact, the friction force always satisfies $F_{f}\leq \mu N$ , with equality reached only at a critical ramp angle (given by $\tan ^{-1}\mu$ ) that is steep enough to initiate sliding.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The friction coefficient is an empirical (experimentally measured) structural property that depends only on various aspects of the contacting materials, such as surface roughness.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The coefficient of friction is not a function of mass or volume.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] For instance, a large aluminum block has the same coefficient of friction as a small aluminum block.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] However, the magnitude of the friction force itself depends on the normal force, and hence on the mass of the block.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Depending on the situation, the calculation of the normal force N might include forces other than gravity.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] If an object is on a *level surface* and subjected to an external force P tending to cause it to slide, then the normal force between the object and the surface is just $N=mg+P_{y}$ , where $mg$ is the block's weight and $P_{y}$ is the downward component of the external force.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Prior to sliding, this friction force is $F_{f}=-P_{x}$ , where $P_{x}$ is the horizontal component of the external force.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Sliding commences only after this frictional force reaches the value $F_{f}=\mu N$ .
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Until then, friction is whatever it needs to be to provide equilibrium, so it can be treated as simply a reaction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] If the object is on a *tilted surface* such as an inclined plane, the normal force from gravity is smaller than $mg$ , because less of the force of gravity is perpendicular to the face of the plane.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The normal force and the frictional force are ultimately determined using vector analysis, usually via a free body diagram.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In general, process for solving any statics problem with friction is to treat contacting surfaces *tentatively* as immovable so that the corresponding tangential reaction force between them can be calculated.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] If this frictional reaction force satisfies $F_{f}\leq \mu N$ , then the tentative assumption was correct, and it is the actual frictional force.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Otherwise, the friction force must be set equal to $F_{f}=\mu N$ , and then the resulting force imbalance would then determine the acceleration associated with slipping.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] For certain applications, it is more useful to define static friction in terms of the maximum angle before which one of the items will begin sliding.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This is called the *angle of friction* or *friction angle*.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] It is defined as: $\tan {\theta }=\mu _{\mathrm {s} }$ and thus: $\theta =\arctan {\mu _{\mathrm {s} }}$ where $\theta$ is the angle from horizontal and *μs* is the static coefficient of friction between the objects.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This formula can also be used to calculate *μs* from empirical measurements of the friction angle.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The **coefficient of friction** (COF), often symbolized by the Greek letter μ, is a dimensionless scalar value which equals the ratio of the force of friction between two bodies and the force pressing them together, either during or at the onset of slipping.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The coefficient of friction depends on the materials used; for example, ice on steel has a low coefficient of friction, while rubber on pavement has a high coefficient of friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Coefficients of friction range from near zero to greater than one.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The coefficient of friction between two surfaces of similar metals is greater than that between two surfaces of different metals; for example, brass has a higher coefficient of friction when moved against brass, but less if moved against steel or aluminum.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] For surfaces at rest relative to each other, $\mu =\mu _{\mathrm {s} }$ , where $\mu _{\mathrm {s} }$ is the *coefficient of static friction*.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This is usually larger than its kinetic counterpart.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The fractality of surfaces, a parameter describing the scaling behavior of surface asperities, is known to play an important role in determining the magnitude of the static friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] For surfaces in relative motion $\mu =\mu _{\mathrm {k} }$ , where $\mu _{\mathrm {k} }$ is the *coefficient of kinetic friction*.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The Coulomb friction is equal to $F_{\mathrm {f} }$ , and the frictional force on each surface is exerted in the direction opposite to its motion relative to the other surface.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Arthur Morin introduced the term and demonstrated the utility of the coefficient of friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The coefficient of friction is an empirical measurement—it has to be measured experimentally, and cannot be found through calculations.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Rougher surfaces tend to have higher effective values.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Both static and kinetic coefficients of friction depend on the pair of surfaces in contact; for a given pair of surfaces, the coefficient of static friction is *usually* larger than that of kinetic friction; in some sets the two coefficients are equal, such as teflon-on-teflon.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Most dry materials in combination have friction coefficient values between 0.3 and 0.6.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Values outside this range are rarer, but teflon, for example, can have a coefficient as low as 0.04.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] A value of zero would mean no friction at all, an elusive property.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Rubber in contact with other surfaces can yield friction coefficients from 1 to 2.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Occasionally it is maintained that *μ* is always < 1, but this is not true.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] While in most relevant applications *μ* < 1, a value above 1 merely implies that the force required to slide an object along the surface is greater than the normal force of the surface on the object.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] For example, silicone rubber or acrylic rubber-coated surfaces have a coefficient of friction that can be substantially larger than 1.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] While it is often stated that the coefficient of friction is a "material property", it is better categorized as a "system property".
[src:box2d-physics/friction] For example, a copper pin sliding against a thick copper plate can have a coefficient of friction that varies from 0.6 at low speeds (metal sliding against metal) to below 0.2 at high speeds when the copper surface begins to melt due to frictional heating.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The latter speed, of course, does not determine the coefficient of friction uniquely; if the pin diameter is increased so that the frictional heating is removed rapidly, the temperature drops, the pin remains solid, and the coefficient of friction rises to that of a 'low speed' test.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In systems with significant non-uniform stress fields, because local slip occurs before the system slides, the macroscopic coefficient of static friction depends on the applied load, system size, or shape; Amontons' law is not satisfied macroscopically.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Friction is due to a range of energy dissipative processes.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The base model, first detailed by Bowden and Tabor is that it involves contact of small protusions on surfaces called asperities.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] As the load increases the number and the area of asperity contacts increases, leading to the normal force dependence of friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] As these asperities slide past each other both plastic and elastic deformation processes take place, among others.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The frictional force is the energy dissipated per unit distance by these, the net result often being the linear Coulomb formula mentioned earlier.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Experimental studies of dry sliding friction in engineering materials have shown that friction and wear are controlled not only by the nominal contact conditions, but also by near-surface microstructural evolution, debris generation and tribochemical transformations during sliding.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Reviews and experimental studies have shown that plastic deformation, fracture, material transfer, mechanical mixing and oxidation can all contribute to the transition between mild and severe wear regimes in dry metal contacts.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The importance of debris and “third-body” material formed in the contact has also been demonstrated experimentally, since compacted triboparticulates may either accelerate damage or form protective interfacial layers that reduce direct metal-to-metal contact.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In steels, dry sliding tests have shown that hardness level, load and sliding speed can strongly influence friction stability and wear rate, while oxidative wear may become dominant under suitable sliding conditions.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Experimental investigations further indicate that environmental factors such as hydrogen charging, lubrication regime and cyclic loading may significantly influence crack initiation mechanisms and friction stability in structural alloys.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Despite being a simplified model of friction, the Coulomb model is useful in many numerical simulation applications such as multibody systems and granular material.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Some quite nonlinear effects, such as the so-called Painlevé paradoxes, may be encountered with Coulomb friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The Coulomb approximation is fundamentally an empirical construct.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] It is a rule-of-thumb describing the approximate outcome of an extremely complicated physical interaction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The strength of the approximation is its simplicity and versatility.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Though the relationship between normal force and frictional force is not exactly linear (and so the frictional force is not entirely independent of the contact area of the surfaces), the Coulomb approximation is an adequate representation of friction for the analysis of many physical systems.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] When the surfaces are conjoined, Coulomb friction becomes a very poor approximation (for example, adhesive tape resists sliding even when there is no normal force, or a negative normal force).
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In this case, the frictional force may depend strongly on the area of contact.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Some drag racing tires are adhesive for this reason.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] However, despite the complexity of the fundamental physics behind friction, the relationships are accurate enough to be useful in many applications.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Dry friction can induce several types of instabilities in mechanical systems which display a stable behaviour in the absence of friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The latter were originally discovered in 1995 by George G.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Adams and João Arménio Correia Martins for smooth surfaces and were later found in periodic rough surfaces.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In particular, friction-related dynamical instabilities are thought to be responsible for brake squeal and the 'song' of a glass harp, phenomena which involve stick and slip, modelled as a drop of friction coefficient with velocity.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] A practically important case is the self-oscillation of the strings of bowed instruments such as the violin, cello, hurdy-gurdy, erhu, etc.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] A connection between dry friction and flutter instability in a simple mechanical system has been discovered, watch the movie Archived 2025-12-11 at the Wayback Machine for more details.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Frictional instabilities can lead to the formation of new self-organized patterns (or "secondary structures") at the sliding interface, such as in-situ formed tribofilms which are utilized for the reduction of friction and wear in so-called self-lubricating materials.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In 2008 scientists for the first time were able to move a single atom across a surface, and measure the forces required.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Using ultrahigh vacuum and nearly zero temperature (5 K), a modified atomic force microscope was used to drag a cobalt atom, and a carbon monoxide molecule, across surfaces of copper and platinum.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] As of 2012, a single study has demonstrated the potential for an *effectively negative coefficient of friction in the low-load regime*, meaning that a decrease in normal force leads to an increase in friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This contradicts everyday experience in which an increase in normal force leads to an increase in friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This was reported in the journal *Nature* in October 2012 and involved the friction encountered by an atomic force microscope stylus when dragged across a graphene sheet in the presence of graphene-adsorbed oxygen.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The origin of kinetic friction at nanoscale can be rationalized by an energy model.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] During sliding, a new surface forms at the back of a sliding true contact, and existing surface disappears at the front of it.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Since all surfaces involve the thermodynamic surface energy, work must be spent in creating the new surface, and energy is released as heat in removing the surface.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Thus, a force is required to move the back of the contact, and frictional heat is released at the front.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Under certain conditions some materials have very low friction coefficients.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] An example is (highly ordered pyrolytic) graphite which can have a friction coefficient below 0.01.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This ultralow-friction regime is called superlubricity.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Fluid friction occurs between fluid layers that are moving relative to each other.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This internal resistance to flow is named *viscosity*.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In everyday terms, the viscosity of a fluid is described as its "thickness".
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Thus, water is "thin", having a lower viscosity, while honey is "thick", having a higher viscosity.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The less viscous the fluid, the greater its ease of deformation or movement.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] All real fluids (except superfluids) offer some resistance to shearing and therefore are viscous.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] For teaching and explanatory purposes it is helpful to use the concept of an inviscid fluid or an ideal fluid which offers no resistance to shearing and so is not viscous.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Lubricated friction is a case of fluid friction where a fluid separates two solid surfaces.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Lubrication is a technique employed to reduce wear of one or both surfaces in close proximity moving relative to each another by interposing a substance called a lubricant between the surfaces.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In most cases the applied load is carried by pressure generated within the fluid due to the frictional viscous resistance to motion of the lubricating fluid between the surfaces.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Adequate lubrication allows smooth continuous operation of equipment, with only mild wear, and without excessive stresses or seizures at bearings.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] When lubrication breaks down, metal or other components can rub destructively over each other, causing heat and possibly damage or failure.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Skin friction arises from the interaction between the fluid and the skin of an object, and is directly related to the area of the surface of the body that is in contact with the fluid.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Skin friction follows the drag equation and rises with the square of the velocity.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Skin friction is caused by viscous drag in the boundary layer around the object.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] There are two ways to decrease skin friction: the first is to shape the moving body so that smooth flow is possible, like an airfoil.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The second method is to decrease the length and cross-section of the moving object as much as is practicable.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Internal friction is the force resisting motion between the elements making up a solid material while it undergoes deformation.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The best understood case is the drag force on dislocations due to atomic vibrations (phonon drag), although electron interactions can also play a role.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] There are also contributions from dissipative forces on the motion of grain boundaries in metals, and there are similar phenomena in vitreous materials such as glasses.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] As a consequence of light pressure, Einstein in 1909 predicted the existence of "radiation friction" which would oppose the movement of matter.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] He wrote, "radiation will exert pressure on both sides of the plate.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The forces of pressure exerted on the two sides are equal if the plate is at rest.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] However, if it is in motion, more radiation will be reflected on the surface that is ahead during the motion (front surface) than on the back surface.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The backward-acting force of pressure exerted on the front surface is thus larger than the force of pressure acting on the back.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Hence, as the resultant of the two forces, there remains a force that counteracts the motion of the plate and that increases with the velocity of the plate.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Rolling resistance is the force that resists the rolling of a wheel or other circular object along a surface caused by deformations in the object or surface.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Generally the force of rolling resistance is less than that associated with kinetic friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Typical values for the coefficient of rolling resistance for steel wheels on a track are 0.001.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] One of the most common examples of rolling resistance, with a coefficient of around 0.02, is the movement of motor vehicle tires on a road, a process which generates heat and sound as by-products.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Any wheel equipped with a brake is capable of generating a large retarding force, usually for the purpose of slowing and stopping a vehicle or piece of rotating machinery.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Braking friction differs from rolling friction because the coefficient of friction for rolling friction is small whereas the coefficient of friction for braking friction is designed to be large by choice of materials for brake pads.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Rubbing two materials against each other can lead to charge transfer, either electrons or ions.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The energy required for this contributes to the friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In addition, sliding can cause a build-up of electrostatic charge, which can be hazardous if flammable gases or vapours are present.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] When the static build-up discharges, explosions can be caused by ignition of the flammable mixture.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] However, as discussed recently the extent to which triboelectricity contributes to friction is contentious, with some claims that it is large, others that it is small because charge transfer can occur with superlubricious samples.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Belt friction is a physical property observed from the forces acting on a belt wrapped around a pulley, when one end is being pulled.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The resulting tension, which acts on both ends of the belt, can be modeled by the belt friction equation.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] In practice, the theoretical tension acting on the belt or rope calculated by the belt friction equation can be compared to the maximum tension the belt can support.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This helps a designer of such a rig to know how many times the belt or rope must be wrapped around the pulley to prevent it from slipping.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Mountain climbers and sailing crews demonstrate a standard knowledge of belt friction when accomplishing basic tasks.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Devices such as wheels, ball bearings, roller bearings, and air cushion or other types of fluid bearings can change sliding friction into a much smaller type of rolling friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Many thermoplastic materials such as nylon, HDPE and PTFE are commonly used in low friction bearings.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] They are especially useful because the coefficient of friction falls with increasing imposed load.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] For improved wear resistance, very high molecular weight grades are usually specified for heavy duty or critical bearings.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] A common way to reduce friction is by using a lubricant, such as oil, water, or grease, which is placed between the two surfaces, often dramatically lessening the coefficient of friction.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] The science of friction and lubrication is called tribology.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Lubricant technology is when lubricants are mixed with the application of science, especially to industrial or commercial objectives.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Superlubricity, a recently discovered effect, has been observed in graphite: it is the substantial decrease of friction between two sliding objects, approaching zero levels.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] A very small amount of frictional energy would still be dissipated.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Lubricants to overcome friction need not always be thin, turbulent fluids or powdery solids such as graphite and talc; acoustic lubrication actually uses sound as a lubricant.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Another way to reduce friction between two parts is to superimpose micro-scale vibration to one of the parts.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] This can be sinusoidal vibration as used in ultrasound-assisted cutting or vibration noise, known as dither.
[src:box2d-physics/friction] Friction is an important factor in many engineering disciplines.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] In classical mechanics, **impulse** (symbolized by **J** or **Imp**) is the change in momentum of an object.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] It is most often used to describe forces which act over short time periods, specifically in the case of impacts and collisions, for which it gets its namesake.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] Impulse is a vector quantity, meaning it has both a magnitude, which describes the amount by which the momentum changed, and a direction, which describes the direction in which the momentum changed.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] For a force acting over a short time, the impulse is often *idealized* so that the change in momentum produced by the force is modelled as happening instantaneously.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] This sort of change is a step change, and is not physically possible.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] However, this is a useful model for computing the effects of ideal collisions (such as in videogame physics engines).
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] Additionally, in rocketry, the term "total impulse" is commonly used and is considered synonymous with the term "impulse".
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] Impulse has the same units and dimensions (LMT−1) as momentum.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] The SI unit of impulse is the newton-second (N⋅s), and the dimensionally equivalent unit of momentum is the kilogram-metre per second (kg⋅m/s).
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] The corresponding English engineering unit is the pound-second (lbf⋅s), and in the British Gravitational System, the unit is the slug-foot per second (slug⋅ft/s).
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] This is often called the impulse–momentum theorem (analogous to the work–energy theorem).
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] As a result of the previous result, an impulse may also be regarded as the change in momentum of an object to which a resultant force is applied.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] The application of Newton's second law for variable mass allows impulse and momentum to be used as analysis tools for jet- or rocket-propelled vehicles.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] In the case of rockets, the impulse imparted can be normalized by unit of propellant expended, to create a performance parameter, specific impulse, the impulse per unit mass.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] This fact can be used to derive the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation, which relates the vehicle's propulsive change in velocity to the engine's specific impulse (or nozzle exhaust velocity) and the vehicle's propellant-mass ratio.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] Newton's second law is often written as $\mathbf {F} ={\frac {\mathrm {d} \mathbf {p} }{\mathrm {d} t}}.$ But this is the case only when there is no mass *transfer* into or out of **p**.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] When the mass of an object changes by exuding or accumulating mass, the momentum has a time dependence in its mass aspect as well as in its velocity aspect.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] Thus, using either the step-wise impulse method or the infinitesimal Newtonian force method work in this case.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] Suppose our previous example was for a rocket.
[src:box2d-physics/impulse-physics] Then, using the equation for **J**, we have that the specific impulse *I*sp is $I_{\mathrm {sp} }=\mathbf {v} -\mathbf {u} .$ In this case, we call this quantity the exhaust velocity since it is equal to the velocity at which the material is leaving the rocket relative to the frame of the rocket.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] A **physics engine** is computer software that provides an approximate simulation of certain physical systems, typically classical dynamics, including rigid body dynamics (including collision detection), soft body dynamics, and fluid dynamics.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] It is of use in the domains of computer graphics, video games and film (CGI).
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Their main uses are in video games (typically as middleware), in which case the simulations are in real-time.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] The term is sometimes used more generally to describe any software system for simulating physical phenomena, such as high-performance scientific simulation.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] There are generally two classes of physics engines: real-time and high-precision.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] High-precision physics engines require more processing power to calculate very precise physics and are usually used by scientists and prerendered computer animation, such as movies.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Real-time physics engines—as used in video games and other forms of interactive computing—use simplified calculations and decreased accuracy to compute in time for the game to respond at an appropriate rate for game play.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] A physics engine is essentially a big calculator that does mathematics needed to simulate physics.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] One of the first general purpose computers, ENIAC, was used as a very simple type of physics engine.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] It was used to design ballistics tables to help the United States military estimate where artillery shells of various mass would land when fired at varying angles and gunpowder charges, also accounting for drift caused by wind.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] The results were calculated a single time only, and were tabulated into printed tables handed out to the artillery commanders.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Physics engines have been commonly used on supercomputers since the 1980s to perform computational fluid dynamics modeling, where particles are assigned force vectors that are combined to show circulation.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Due to the requirements of speed and high precision, special computer processors known as vector processors were developed to accelerate the calculations.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] The techniques can be used to model weather patterns in weather forecasting, wind tunnel data for designing air- and watercraft or motor vehicles including racecars, and thermal cooling of computer processors for improving heat sinks.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] As with many calculation-laden processes in computing, the accuracy of the simulation is related to the resolution of the simulation and the precision of the calculations; small fluctuations not modeled in the simulation can drastically change the predicted results.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Tire manufacturers use physics simulations to examine how new tire tread types will perform under wet and dry conditions, using new tire materials of varying flexibility and under different levels of weight loading.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] The simulations optimize tire operations, material selection, costs, and enhance time efficiency.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] In most computer games, speed of the processors and gameplay are more important than accuracy of simulation.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] This leads to designs for physics engines that produce results in real-time but that replicate real world physics only for simple cases and typically with some approximation.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] More often than not, the simulation is geared towards providing a "perceptually correct" approximation rather than a real simulation.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] However some game engines, such as Source, use physics in puzzles or in combat situations.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] This requires more accurate physics so that, for example, the momentum of an object can knock over an obstacle or lift a sinking object.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Physically-based character animation in the past only used rigid body dynamics because they are faster and easier to calculate, but modern games and movies are starting to use soft body physics.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Soft body physics are also used for particle effects, liquids and cloth.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Some form of limited fluid dynamics simulation is sometimes provided to simulate water and other liquids as well as the flow of fire and explosions through the air.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Objects in games interact with the player, the environment, and each other.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Typically, most 3D objects in games are represented by two separate meshes or shapes.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] One of these meshes is the highly complex and detailed shape visible to the player in the game, such as a vase with elegant curved and looping handles.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] For purpose of speed, a second, simplified invisible mesh is used to represent the object to the physics engine so that the physics engine treats the example vase as a simple cylinder.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] It would thus be impossible to insert a rod or fire a projectile through the handle holes on the vase, because the physics engine model is based on the cylinder and is unaware of the handles.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] The simplified mesh used for physics processing is often referred to as the collision geometry.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] This may be a bounding box, sphere, or convex hull.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Engines that use bounding boxes or bounding spheres as the final shape for collision detection are considered extremely simple.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Generally a bounding box is used for broad phase collision detection to narrow down the number of possible collisions before costly mesh on mesh collision detection is done in the narrow phase of collision detection.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Another aspect of precision in discrete collision detection involves the framerate, or the number of moments in time per second when physics is calculated.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Each frame is treated as separate from all other frames, and the space between frames is not calculated.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] A low framerate and a small fast-moving object causes a situation where the object does not move smoothly through space but instead seems to teleport from one point in space to the next as each frame is calculated.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Projectiles moving at sufficiently high speeds will miss targets, if the target is small enough to fit in the gap between the calculated frames of the fast moving projectile.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Various techniques are used to overcome this flaw, such as *Second Life*'s representation of projectiles as arrows with invisible trailing tails longer than the gap in frames to collide with any object that might fit between the calculated frames.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] By contrast, continuous collision detection such as in Bullet or Havok does not suffer this problem.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] An alternative to using bounding box-based rigid body physics systems is to use a finite element-based system.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] In such a system, a 3-dimensional, volumetric tessellation is created of the 3D object.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] The tessellation results in a number of finite elements which represent aspects of the object's physical properties such as toughness, plasticity, and volume preservation.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Once constructed, the finite elements are used by a solver to model the stress within the 3D object.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] The stress can be used to drive fracture, deformation and other physical effects with a high degree of realism and uniqueness.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] As the number of modeled elements is increased, the engine's ability to model physical behavior increases.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] The visual representation of the 3D object is altered by the finite element system through the use of a deformation shader run on the CPU or GPU.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Finite Element-based systems had been impractical for use in games due to the performance overhead and the lack of tools to create finite element representations out of 3D art objects.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] James O'Brien as a part of his PhD thesis.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] In the real world, physics is always active.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] There is a constant Brownian motion jitter to all particles in our universe as the forces push back and forth against each other.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] For a game physics engine, such constant active precision is unnecessarily wasting the limited CPU power, which can cause problems such as decreased framerate.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Thus, games may put objects to "sleep" by disabling the computation of physics on objects that have not moved a particular distance within a certain amount of time.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] For example, in the 3D virtual world Second Life, if an object is resting on the floor and the object does not move beyond a minimal distance in about two seconds, then the physics calculations are disabled for the object and it becomes frozen in place.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] The object remains frozen until physics processing reactivates for the object after collision occurs with some other active physical object.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Physics engines for video games typically have two core components, a collision detection/collision response system, and the dynamics simulation component responsible for solving the forces affecting the simulated objects.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Modern physics engines may also contain fluid simulations, animation control systems and asset integration tools.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Finally, hybrid methods are possible that combine aspects of the above paradigms.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] A primary limit of physics engine realism is the approximated result of the constraint resolutions and collision result due to the slow convergence of algorithms.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Collision detection computed at a too low frequency can result in objects passing through each other and then being repelled with an abnormal correction force.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] On the other hand, approximated results of reaction force is due to the slow convergence of typical Projected Gauss Seidel solver resulting in abnormal bouncing.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Any type of free-moving compound physics object can demonstrate this problem, but it is especially prone to affecting chain links under high tension, and wheeled objects with actively physical bearing surfaces.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Higher precision reduces the positional/force errors, but at the cost of needing greater CPU power for the calculations.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] A physics processing unit (PPU) is a dedicated microprocessor designed to handle the calculations of physics, especially in the physics engine of video games.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Examples of calculations involving a PPU might include rigid body dynamics, soft body dynamics, collision detection, fluid dynamics, hair and clothing simulation, finite element analysis, and fracturing of objects.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] The idea is that specialized processors offload time-consuming tasks from a computer's CPU, much like how a GPU performs graphics operations in the main CPU's place.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] The term was coined by Ageia's marketing to describe their PhysX chip to consumers.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Several other technologies in the CPU-GPU spectrum have some features in common with it, although Ageia's solution was the only complete one designed, marketed, supported, and placed within a system *exclusively* as a PPU.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] Hardware acceleration for physics processing is now usually provided by graphics processing units that support more general computation, a concept known as general-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU).
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] AMD and NVIDIA provide support for rigid body dynamics computations on their latest graphics cards.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] NVIDIA's GeForce 8 series supports a GPU-based Newtonian physics acceleration technology named *Quantum Effects Technology*.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] NVIDIA provides an SDK Toolkit for CUDA (Compute Unified Device Architecture) technology that offers both a low and high-level API to the GPU.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] For their GPUs, AMD offers a similar SDK, called Close to Metal (CTM), which provides a thin hardware interface.
[src:box2d-physics/physics-engine] PhysX is an example of a physics engine that can use GPGPU based hardware acceleration when it is available.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In classical mechanics, **rigid body dynamics** studies the movement of systems of interconnected bodies under the action of external forces.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Along with statics, it forms the field of **rigid body mechanics**.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The assumption that the bodies are *rigid* (i.e. they do not deform under the action of applied forces) simplifies analysis, by reducing the parameters that describe the configuration of the system to the translation and rotation of body-fixed frames.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This excludes bodies that display fluid, highly elastic, and plastic behavior.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of a rigid body system is described by the laws of kinematics and by the application of Newton's second law (kinetics) or their derivative form, Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution of these equations of motion provides a description of the position, the motion and the acceleration of the individual components of the system, and overall the system itself, as a function of time.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The formulation and solution of rigid body dynamics is an important tool in the computer simulation of mechanical systems.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of particles moves parallel to a fixed plane, the system is said to be constrained to planar movement.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, Newton's laws (kinetics) for a rigid system of N particles, P*i*, *i*=1,...,*N*, simplify because there is no movement in the *k* direction.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where **r**i denotes the planar trajectory of each particle.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] For systems that are constrained to planar movement, the angular velocity and angular acceleration vectors are directed along **k** perpendicular to the plane of movement, which simplifies this acceleration equation.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {e} _{i}=0}$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {t} _{i}=\mathbf {k} }$ is the unit vector perpendicular to the plane for all of the particles Pi.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where M is the total mass and *I***C** is the moment of inertia about an axis perpendicular to the movement of the rigid system and through the center of mass.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Several methods to describe orientations of a rigid body in three dimensions have been developed.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] They are summarized in the following sections.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The first attempt to represent an orientation is attributed to Leonhard Euler.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The values of these three rotations are called Euler angles.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Commonly, $\psi$ is used to denote precession, $\theta$ nutation, and $\phi$ intrinsic rotation.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] These are three angles, also known as yaw, pitch and roll, Navigation angles and Cardan angles.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Mathematically they constitute a set of six possibilities inside the twelve possible sets of Euler angles, the ordering being the one best used for describing the orientation of a vehicle such as an airplane.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In aerospace engineering they are usually referred to as Euler angles.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Euler also realized that the composition of two rotations is equivalent to a single rotation about a different fixed axis (Euler's rotation theorem).
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, the composition of the former three angles has to be equal to only one rotation, whose axis was complicated to calculate until matrices were developed.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Based on this fact he introduced a vectorial way to describe any rotation, with a vector on the rotation axis and module equal to the value of the angle.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, any orientation can be represented by a rotation vector (also called Euler vector) that leads to it from the reference frame.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, the rotation vector is commonly called orientation vector, or attitude vector.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] A similar method, called axis-angle representation, describes a rotation or orientation using a unit vector aligned with the rotation axis, and a separate value to indicate the angle (see figure).
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] With the introduction of matrices the Euler theorems were rewritten.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The rotations were described by orthogonal matrices referred to as rotation matrices or direction cosine matrices.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, a rotation matrix is commonly called orientation matrix, or attitude matrix.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The above-mentioned Euler vector is the eigenvector of a rotation matrix (a rotation matrix has a unique real eigenvalue).
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The product of two rotation matrices is the composition of rotations.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, as before, the orientation can be given as the rotation from the initial frame to achieve the frame that we want to describe.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The configuration space of a non-symmetrical object in *n*-dimensional space is SO(*n*) × **R***n*.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Orientation may be visualized by attaching a basis of tangent vectors to an object.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The direction in which each vector points determines its orientation.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Another way to describe rotations is using rotation quaternions, also called versors.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] They are equivalent to rotation matrices and rotation vectors.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] With respect to rotation vectors, they can be more easily converted to and from matrices.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent orientations, rotation quaternions are typically called orientation quaternions or attitude quaternions.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] To consider rigid body dynamics in three-dimensional space, Newton's second law must be extended to define the relationship between the movement of a rigid body and the system of forces and torques that act on it.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The extension of Newton's second law to rigid bodies is achieved by considering a rigid system of particles.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of *N* particles, Pi, i=1,...,*N*, are assembled into a rigid body, then Newton's second law can be applied to each of the particles in the body.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] An important simplification to these force equations is obtained by introducing the resultant force and torque that acts on the rigid system.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This resultant force and torque is obtained by choosing one of the particles in the system as a reference point, **R**, where each of the external forces are applied with the addition of an associated torque.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The resultant force **F** and torque **T** are given by the formulas, $\mathbf {F} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}\mathbf {F} _{i},\quad \mathbf {T} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}(\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )\times \mathbf {F} _{i},$ where **R**i is the vector that defines the position of particle Pi.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The mass properties of the rigid body are represented by its center of mass and inertia matrix.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] then it is known as the center of mass of the system.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the column vector **R**i − **R**; $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is its transpose, and $\mathbf {I}$ is the 3 by 3 identity matrix.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the scalar product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself, while $\mathbf {S} _{i}\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is the tensor product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Using the center of mass and inertia matrix, the force and torque equations for a single rigid body take the form $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a} ,\quad \mathbf {T} =[I_{R}]\alpha +\omega \times [I_{R}]\omega ,$ and are known as Newton's second law of motion for a rigid body.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of an interconnected system of rigid bodies, *B**i*, *j* = 1, ..., *M*, is formulated by isolating each rigid body and introducing the interaction forces.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Newton's formulation yields 6*M* equations that define the dynamics of a system of *M* rigid bodies.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] A rotating object, whether under the influence of torques or not, may exhibit the behaviours of precession and nutation.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution to this equation when there is no applied torque is discussed in the articles Euler's equation of motion and Poinsot's ellipsoid.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] It follows from Euler's equation that a torque **τ** applied perpendicular to the axis of rotation, and therefore perpendicular to **L**, results in a rotation about an axis perpendicular to both **τ** and **L**.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Precession can be demonstrated by placing a spinning top with its axis horizontal and supported loosely (frictionless toward precession) at one end.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Instead of falling, as might be expected, the top appears to defy gravity by remaining with its axis horizontal, when the other end of the axis is left unsupported and the free end of the axis slowly describes a circle in a horizontal plane, the resulting precession turning.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This effect is explained by the above equations.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The torque on the top is supplied by a couple of forces: gravity acting downward on the device's centre of mass, and an equal force acting upward to support one end of the device.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Under a constant torque of magnitude *τ*, the speed of precession *Ω*P is inversely proportional to *L*, the magnitude of its angular momentum: $\tau ={\mathit {\Omega }}_{\mathrm {P} }L\sin \theta ,$ where *θ* is the angle between the vectors **Ω**P and **L**.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, if the top's spin slows down (for example, due to friction), its angular momentum decreases and so the rate of precession increases.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This continues until the device is unable to rotate fast enough to support its own weight, when it stops precessing and falls off its support, mostly because friction against precession cause another precession that goes to cause the fall.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] By convention, these three vectors – torque, spin, and precession – are all oriented with respect to each other according to the right-hand rule.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] An alternate formulation of rigid body dynamics that has a number of convenient features is obtained by considering the virtual work of forces acting on a rigid body.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The virtual work of forces acting at various points on a single rigid body can be calculated using the velocities of their point of application and the resultant force and torque.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The trajectories of **R***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n* are defined by the movement of the rigid body.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The velocity of the points **R***i* along their trajectories are $\mathbf {V} _{i}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}\times (\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where **ω** is the angular velocity vector of the body.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] is known as the generalized force associated with the virtual displacement δq.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] It is useful to note that conservative forces such as gravity and spring forces are derivable from a potential function *V*(*q*1, ..., *q**n*), known as a potential energy.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The equations of motion for a mechanical system of rigid bodies can be determined using D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The principle of virtual work is used to study the static equilibrium of a system of rigid bodies; however, by introducing acceleration terms in Newton's laws this approach is generalized to define dynamic equilibrium.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The static equilibrium of a mechanical system rigid bodies is defined by the condition that the virtual work of the applied forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This is known as the *principle of virtual work.* This is equivalent to the requirement that the generalized forces for any virtual displacement are zero, that is *Q**i*=0.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Let a mechanical system be constructed from n rigid bodies, B*i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, and let the resultant of the applied forces on each body be the force-torque pairs, **F***i* and **T***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Notice that these applied forces do not include the reaction forces where the bodies are connected.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Finally, assume that the velocity **V***i* and angular velocities ***ω****i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, for each rigid body, are defined by a single generalized coordinate q.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Such a system of rigid bodies is said to have one degree of freedom.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] These m equations define the static equilibrium of the system of rigid bodies.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Consider a single rigid body which moves under the action of a resultant force **F** and torque **T**, with one degree of freedom defined by the generalized coordinate *q*.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work states that a system of rigid bodies is in dynamic equilibrium when the virtual work of the sum of the applied forces and the inertial forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, dynamic equilibrium of a system of n rigid bodies with m generalized coordinates requires that $\delta W=\left(Q_{1}+Q_{1}^{*}\right)\delta q_{1}+\dots +\left(Q_{m}+Q_{m}^{*}\right)\delta q_{m}=0,$ for any set of virtual displacements *δq**j*.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, introduce the Lagrangian, *L* = *T* − *V*, so these equations of motion become ${\frac {d}{dt}}{\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}_{j}}}-{\frac {\partial L}{\partial q_{j}}}=0\quad j=1,\ldots ,m.$ These are known as Lagrange's equations of motion.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The linear and angular momentum of a rigid system of particles is formulated by measuring the position and velocity of the particles relative to the center of mass.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Let the system of particles Pi, *i* = 1, ..., *n* be located at the coordinates **r***i* and velocities **v***i*.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] To specialize these formulas to a rigid body, assume the particles are rigidly connected to each other so Pi, i=1,...,n are located by the coordinates **r**i and velocities **v**i.
[src:box2d-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Select a reference point **R** and compute the relative position and velocity vectors, $\mathbf {r} _{i}=(\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {R} ,\quad \mathbf {v} _{i}=\omega \times (\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where ω is the angular velocity of the system.
